Re:


15 May 2009 02:26






I put it there because I've always been a strong believer that documents referred to in an article should leave SOME trace behind, even if not written. I also figured that it was a log of ALL incidents caused by SCP-343, not just a detailed summary of one of them, so I left it as Incident Log 343. I have no idea what Paradox was referring to when he put in the bit about atypical incidents: I assumed he meant (relatively) ordinary stuff like teleporting on top of buildings, nothing destructive. Typical stuff for the Foundation, but stuff that would alarm the populace.

I've always wondered about the "good-cop, bad-cop" routine: for some reason the idea comes to mind of a seemingly-omnipotent alien being taken off the case by a galactic review board after examination of his little "stunts", like vaporisation of Sodom/Gomorrah, drowning of Egyptian armies, etc. and replaced by one with a gentler approach and a softer tone. Perhaps 343 is an example of this, an equally-mortal alien sent down to evaluate the progress of the Earth Civilization project. Perhaps he's not the Judeo-Christian God, but a deity nonetheless. Perhaps he's an imposter with magic powers. Perhaps, and this is the one I had in mind when I initially read it, he's a creator content to sit back and observe. All of these interpretations are equally plausible, and this is why the Foundation panics.

In any case, he doesn't seem very angry or vengeful at the moment. Kind of a Morgan Freeman incarnation. What makes this article, in my opinion, is the uncertainty of the situation, how he could be any number of things at the same time, perhaps just waiting for his chance, waiting for a reply from his brethren, or maybe he'll just be content to sit and talk forever.







