28 Jun 2009 00:53






By "the old version", I'm referring to the version before the version before your edit. Revision number 8, according to the article history.

I never got any impression that 343 was actively drawing people towards it - it seemed to me that "God" was simply a wonderful conversationalist (and, well, allegedly God), so people naturally wanted to talk to him.

Dr. Beck's request was indeed "odd" because asking regular staff to interact with an extremely powerful sentient SCP for reasons other than containment or experimentation is really abnormal. That the request was granted anyway is more a reflection on 343 being perfectly benign and beneficial then on things being fishy.

As for Document #343-1a, Document #343-1b, and Addendum #343-2, the bit mentioning "This is the last straw Dr.B…[DATA LOST]" implies that Dr. Beck was the one removing files and otherwise preventing Dr. Whoever from adding restrictions, quite possibly out of a sincere (and uninfluenced) belief that doing so was a ridiculous waste of time (and might do more harm then good).

The bit with the guards saying "You know He likes company" could be construed as them being puppets - or it could simply be that 343 promised them they'd never get in trouble for abandoning their posts, and since he's a) capable of ensuring that, b) a nice guy, and c) most likely The Guy What Makes The Rules in whatever faiths the guards might follow, they said to themselves, "Sure, why not?"

The bit with no one remembering Dr. What's-his-name could be construed as 343 having made him dissappear - or it could simply be that Dr. So-and-so had never actually interacted with any of the involved staff and just overreacted based on reports he'd read, after which 343 didn't do a thing to him and just fudged up the records and circumstances such that Dr. Beck and others wouldn't get in trouble because of some paranoid spoilsport's objections.

On the face of it, the most "God" ever did was tweak things such that no one would ever get in trouble for talking to him or for allowing others to do so. That the article was written such that a more sinister interpretation is still possible is a benefit. I don't think a major alteration of tone was needed - and if it was, all you'd have to do is change "repeating 'You know He likes company'" to "saying 'You know He likes company' or shrugging" and maybe remove the bit about records of Dr. Name-redacted himself being missing.







